    </div>
    <h2 class="title"><a href="https://orangette.net/2006/01/let-me-eat-cake/">Let me eat cake</a></h2>
  </header>
  <figure class="post-figure hero">
    <a href="https://orangette.net/2006/01/let-me-eat-cake/">
      <img width="320" height="240" src="https://orangette.net/wp-content/uploads/2006/01/Rainy_day_window.1.jpg" class="post__photo" alt="" decoding="async" loading="lazy" />    </a>
  </figure>
  <div class="post__summary">
    <p>When it comes to Seattle’s infamously rainy weather, I’m usually pretty nonchalant. Sure, it may be gray for roughly eight months of the year, but the clouds make a nice, fleecy blanket, insulating us from the frigid winter air that haunts our sunnier brethren at similar latitudes. And anyway, what Seattle calls “rain” is actually more of a mist—just a spittle of sorts, really, and hardly worth the price of an umbrella. But today, dear reader, marks the twenty-fifth consecutive day of rain in our very Emerald City, and, says National Weather Service meteorologist Gary Schneider, “There are no dry days in the foreseeable future.” Yesterday, when a ray of sunlight briefly lit upon my desk, it took every ounce&hellip;</p>
    <a href="https://orangette.net/2006/01/let-me-eat-cake/" class="post-more">Read more</a>
  </div>
</article>
  <article class="post-1691 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized">
  <header class="post-header">
    <div class="kicker">
